76561198046338879,Not Recommended,460920,28532169,"Posted: 22 December, 2016",all,Six-Foot Turkey,"The game was quite fun, however I was quickly becomming bored after trying out each sport. I don't think the game is worth £40 however, since there is no way to play the game offline so if you are suddenly disconnected from the internet, the game will go to the home screen.The game looks great graphically and the animations and design on the map look great. But I find the mentioning of singleplayer on the store page to be quite misleading since singleplayer, to me often implies there is the ability to play offline without other people or an internet connection. Usually games that are only online multiplayer are much cheaper, but this game at full price is a bit much.I don't recommend buying this game at full price or if you have a bad internet connection, but maybe during a sale."
76561198004811351,Recommended,460920,28431305,"Posted: 17 December, 2016",all,AbsoluteDeicide,"Steep is a weird game. A love letter to exploring the picturesque Swiss Alps by way of extreme sports, it toes the line between realism and Red Bull guzzling, MTV goofiness. It's built for scale and spectacle, but digging deeper to actually play the game can feel like you're on a team of beta testers, sharing challenges you pulled out of your♥♥♥♥♥and turning a blind eye to the glaring glitches and rough edges. It suffers from an identity crisis; one minute you'll be paragliding peacefully above a glacier while your avatar narrates a somber diary of conquering the wilderness, fighting oxygen deprivation and dehydration. Then you'll be following a literal ghost rider through the mouths of Ubisoft's Raving Rabbids mascots or being lectured by a stereotypical New York agent for not hitting enough “sick” kickflips. Or a mountain will try to intimidate you, reciting some Robert Frost style poetry. Steep is best played with an open mind. A really open mind...The game can be stunningly gorgeous; the scale of the mountain range is very impressive and boasts some of the most realistic looking representation of snow I've seen. The glittering of the sun off of fresh powder in particular is approaching levels of photorealism. The detail of your character is quite sharp as well, especially considering the vast amount of unlockable accessories available to outfit him/her in. Traversing the frozen environment also leaves convincing tracks as you sink into the drifts, climbing steep slopes to reach points of interest. An applaudable amount of work and artistry went into the snow, but some of the elements surrounding it look out of place. Rocky surfaces can look like smears painted with a broad brush, often visibly, hastily thrown together at artificially rough angles and clipping through each other. Trees and glaciers are carbon copies of each other, leading to stretches of boring, repeating terrain. But the large scale picture is the reason for playing, and these are the compromises of a completely open, load-free playground.You have five modes of transport at your disposal: skiing, snowboarding, paragliding, wing gliding, and walking. Skiing and snowboarding are similar and the challenges that feature them are interchangeable. You have very simple controls with these two: steer with the left stick, the right stick cuts sharply, you hold and release jump to ollie, and from there you can spin and grab. For the most part, though, you're at the mercy of the mountain; it's incredibly difficult to make quick adjustments and it can be a struggle to get your avatar to do what you want to do without serious effort. You have no control over the camera, and that becomes an adversary; jamming to the right trying to hit a checkpoint can easily be undermined by a wild, uncontrollable swing or zoom because the game felt like it. You certainly don't have Tony Hawk/SSX levels of control, which is fine, but what's in Steep is better described as “loose” than simulation. After about twenty hours of playing I felt adjusted to the game's quirks, but more often than not trying to get your rider to generally perform something specific still comes down to trial and error, combating the controls, and a good amount of luck. You're provided with a G-meter that is supposed to track how much punishment you can take before you spill, but in practice the game just does what it wants; a ten second free fall onto solid rock might be okay, but hitting what appears to be a pebble may or may not send you into a knockout faceplant.Wing gliding is the highlight. Flying inches above the ground, weaving around snow covered trees and sharp rocks is exhilarating and it controls responsively. Most of the challenges in the wing suit revolve around passing through rings and gives a serious Pilotwings vibe. Paragliding is more relaxed and is the preferred method for exploring the Alps, allowing you to cover large swaths of land and soak in the sights while you're at it. You're given a very generous updraft system: get close and kinda/sorta perpendicular to a mountainside and there will always be uplift, essentially allowing you to glide endlessly. I'm pretty sure that's not how wind works, but whatever. Walking is where you put one foot in front of the other to initiate locomotion, and while on foot you can use binoculars to spot drop zones and places of interest.The scale and freeform exploration is great, but the “game” part of the game, the challenges, are all over the place. These events are scattered all over the mountains and they're generally races against the clock or score based affairs. They are categorized into Easy, Medium, and Hard difficulties, and you can earn bronze, silver, or gold medals depending on your performance, which awards XP to level up to unlock drop zones and currency to buy cosmetic items. The open nature of the game itself wrecks havoc with any scoring conventions; a single, ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t trick pulled out of your♥♥♥♥♥can destroy a gold medal challenge in seconds. Alternatively, a glitchy camera can be a repeatable bane to finishing a race without ragdolling down a cliff face, and the difference between a gold medal or complete failure can either be a matter of minutes or seconds. There's very little consistency between which challenges will be a fun exercise in sharpening your skills or controller throwing frustration.And that's Steep broadly speaking. It demands to be enjoyed with a relaxed demeanor and forgiving nature from a zoomed out perspective. If you can find that zen state it's one of the best extreme sports games that's released in years. Just don't look at it too closely."
,Recommended,460920,28179986,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,irrel™,"Steep is a gorgeous game.It's beautiful. Once you get past the admittedly repetitive and bland missions, poorly-voiced characters, and a story so shallow it has negative depth, Steep is a sandbox of exploration, tricks, badassery, beauty, and danger.As a note before we begin: Steep is not SSX. You won't find that level of ridiculous stunts here, and the game is not as forgiving. It is comparable to SSX, though, and if you liked SSX, Steep can still offer something to you.Of course, that's when it's at its most poetic. Naturally, the game fills a niche: if you don't like snowboarding, skiing, paragliding, or wingsuiting, you won't like this game, and even if you do, the price is, pardon the pun, rather steep.If you do like them, and the price isn't a problem, you next have to deal with the missions and, consequently, the voice acting. While some of the voices are alright, the grating radio personality and the bland ""boss"" voice are the most frequently heard and the least likeable. The best voices are, thankfully, those of the atheletes (snowboarders? they don't just snowboard).The missions themselves are pleasant at best and teeth-clenchingly frustrating at worst. While the game is difficult on its own, many of the missions are particularly hard, which is poorly-conveyed by the three-star rating system of difficulty. Adding to the problem is that you have to level up to gain access to Mont Blanc, the best mountain for generally having fun, and you have to go through the worst of the mountains to get to it.The ""story"" is as follows: you are a professional extreme sports person, you make money of footage and competitions, you are the best at them, go win and you will unlock more of the competitions. Of course, you shouldn't have expected a story, silly. However, the tone is inconsistent: some missions take themselves seriously like the Red Bull invitationals, but others act like you're on a Hellish game show like the missions of the Mountain of the Damned.The incredible beauty of the game is immediately apparent, though: as soon as you enter, you're dropped in on the mountain range to see the snow-covered hills and glittering snow itself. The graphics are wonderful, and the optimization is pretty solid (my thoughts on optimization are probably not the most reliable, as my rig is pretty high-end). Naturally, though, beauty is subjective, and if you don't like what you see in the screenshots, you won't like what you see in-game.The gameplay is where the game shines, though please read before downvoting because you had a hard time: the game takes some skill and practice. This isn't to say you're bad, this is to say you need to give it time, get used to and good at handling the controls, and note that the keyboard controls are much worse than controller, but the game is entirely playable with mouse and keyboard. Snowboarding and skiing handle mostly cleanly, though inconsistently: sometimes you get slung off to the side when cresting a hill at an awkward angle. The wingsuiting is fast and requires precision, but use the IJKL keys as a second directional pad to dodge and you can slip through gaps you wouldn't be able to before. The only place where the gameplay falls off is with two things: glitches and paragliding. The glitches are maddening at times: sometimes a jump your character landed cleanly and lightly on a steep slope will reduce their endurance gauge (that's the best I can call it) when they should have been fine, and the paragliding is murkily explained with tooltips that don't give any tips at all. The most helpful thing I discovered with paragliding: the stunts button is not just for stunts. It helps you move down in updrafts.Overall, Steep is a beautiful, clean-looking sandbox for high-speed skiing, snowboarding, and wingsuiting, and for leisurely hangtime in paragliding. It's a little unpolished, and you will encounter glitches - perhaps it's best compared to Skate 3 in that regard - but it's a fun, satisfying experience if you're looking for a more modern snowboarding game.TL;DR: Steep is flawed, but it's not bad: the repetitive missions are annoying, the voice acting grates, the keyboard controls are awkward, but once you get past all that and get better at the game, it's a winter wonderland made to be explored and shredded with solid, if slightly inconsistent, handling and beautiful graphics. Use the stunts mode for paragliding if you want to go down fast."
,Recommended,460920,28195671,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,roly!342,overpriced casual fun game.
,Recommended,460920,30719309,Posted: 24 March,all,Jayson ッ,"Ok. Let's break it down.- Good Graphics- Good Multiplayer- Good Mechanics, it feels good and it responds nicely.- Controller is highly preferable- On sale (currently)This game is a really good game if you're an adventurous person. I wouldn't buy it for $60. However, rn it's $30 which is a great deal.Before you buy this, keep this in mind. Steep is essentially this large mountain that you could do whatever you want on. Yes, it will get boring because you are basically doing the same thing over and over again and Yes, you will probably only have about 10-12 hours of actual entertainment. The environment look will grow old. I have a GTX 960M and I can run this game flawlessly on high/ultra graphics.Keyboard and Mouse isn't the best thing to use for this. Being completely honest. You will have way more fun with controller. You can move more accurately with controller as opposed to directly left and right.The wingsuit on keyboard is absolutely aids. You have to constantly hit the Down key (S key) just to remain in the sky. If you get close to ground, you get more points, however, it is more likely that you will get hit and KO'd.Snowboard is alright. You can pretty much do everything alright, but like I said earlier, a controller would be a lot better. Expect to fall on the snowboard a lot because its hard to control the G-force and the way you land on keyboard, for beginners atleast.The ski is basically a replica of the snowboard, however there is only a change in speed. All the movement and everything feels good and its responsive. I don't use the ski's that much so I really don't have a say although in the times i've tried it, those are what i've noticed.I find the parachute to be the easiest to control on keyboard. I prefer to be on the ground going fast on snowboard, but parachute is easy to control, its not that hard to use and you can get some great views from it. Good screenshot material."
,Recommended,460920,28582107,"Posted: 23 December, 2016",all,twillsie,"I bought this game on the winter sale, for what I feel was a fair price. This game is a cross between EA's SKATE and SSX 3 (for the old PS2). Like SKATE, this game takes a serious approach to extreme sports, the tricks can be difficult to pull off and some of the 'lines' (read: levels) are a bit tough, but it is also rewarding. Like SSX3 you get to ski from the top of a gargantuan mountain range to the very bottom, without loading... Seriously no load. You can transport from one end of this insanely large mountain range to the other in a click of a button and it doesn't even load. Bam you're there, bam you're skiing, boarding, skydiving, whatever you want. Well worth the price I paid for it on sale."
