,Recommended,460920,30907282,Posted: 2 April,all,Kemo,"A Steep price for a mountain of funSteep is an extreme winter sports simulator developed by everyone’s favourite company, Ubisoft. (Don’t let that put you off). It predominantly features the Alps but Ubisoft recently introduced some Alaskan slopes too as part of a free update. In Steep you take to the slopes with a snowboard or skis or you take to the skies with a wingsuit or a paraglider. You can complete challenges and events already in the game or you can simply explore the mountain, finding new points of interest, challenges and the best lines you can come up with.When you first get to the Alps, you’ll be struck by the game’s beauty (even if you’re running it on Medium/Low like I am). The dev team did a great job at creating the Alps in-game and you’ll get some truly stunning vistas fairly regularly in the game. Hurtling through a lush forest or gliding your way to a different peak, it’s going to look good. There are some muddier textures which look a bit rough when you get up close (particularly rock textures) but I didn’t see those too often.The ‘main way’ to play the game is through the challenges and events. Of course, you don’t have to these but they are the best way to unlock Steep credits (used to purchase customization options) and earn EXP (some events have level requirements). There are a few different kinds of events. You have Freestyle events (snowboard or skis) in which you have to score a certain amount of points, you also have Extreme Rider events where you score points by narrowly dodging objects. Bonebreaker challenges can be wingsuit or ground events, they feature doing ridiculous things that inevitably lead to you knocking the ever-living♥♥♥♥♥♥out of your rider several times before success (they’re a lot of fun). You also get race events for the wingsuit and paragliding disciplines. There are also some story-ish ‘challenges’ called Mountain Stories which attempt to tell you a story while you complete objectives such as destroying snowmen or following another rider. Personally, I didn’t see the point in trying to tell a story with the game but the challenges themselves are pretty fun.So, as I mentioned, some challenges require scoring a certain number of points to be successful. Unfortunately, the game’s trick controls suck and there are no tutorials to help you. The only tutorials are for how you can ollie and then flip or spin, which is good to know but will net you hardly any points. For snowboarding or skiing it’s all about the grabs you do and the game doesn’t teach you how to do anything other than the most basic grab. I had to look up a separate tutorial to figure out how to do and start getting decent scores on jumps. Getting combos is also very important for racking up high scores, the only way to end a combo is to fall over which happens if you take a few hits (bad landings or riding into an object) or if you just go head first into the ground, that’ll mess you up pretty good surprisingly enough.Now, as much as I enjoy Steep and I think Ubisoft Annecy did a good job with it, there is one part of this game which is simply unforgiveable. It’s always online (and Ubi servers can’t be connected to if you have University WiFi without a VPN connection). It’s one of the most ridiculous design decisions I’ve ever seen in a game. The multiplayer aspect of Steep isn’t even slightly interesting, you can see other riders around the mountain (since you’re always online) and you can group together with them but that just means that the game lets you know what you’re doing and lets you compete with their scores on challenges you’re both doing. Sure, it’s an okay implementation of multiplayer and it can be kind of cool but it most certainly isn’t worth having the game always online. I really hope they add offline functionality before they inevitably shut down the servers. As much as I like the game and want to like Ubisoft for making it, you can’t argue anything other than this is a super ♥♥♥♥♥♥ move on their behalf.As I mentioned earlier, there are a few different rewards for completing challenges. Levelling up your rider is done by earing EXP from challenges which then unlocks new event challenges (like a Red Bull Extreme Rider event) and new Mountain Story events. Some challenges reward you with items such as new helmets, boards, wingsuits etc. that can only be unlocked by completing said challenges. Lastly, you earn Steep credits (the in-game currency) which can be used to buy more items from the in-game store such as ridiculous unicorn costumes, an imp wingsuit as well Helicopter tickets. Helicopter tickets are used to drop you anywhere on the mountain, very handy if you don’t fancy a trek up a steep incline to find a new dropzone. The customization options can be pretty fun to mess around with but they’re definitely not the main focus of the game and it’s really easy to earn Steep credits so there’s no need to pay for microtransactions.One of Steep’s strongest points is how quickly the game changes pace. If you want to find your own line from a dropzone it can be an incredibly relaxing experience that’ll take your mind off of the real world for a while. It can also be a controller smashingly infuriating game when you’re playing the hardest challenges, failing time and time again before you finally get the sweet satisfaction of beating the challenge.Last but not least, this is not a $60 game. I paid $30 for the base game which I’m happy with but I think I’d probably feel different about the game if I had dropped $60 on it. There’s a lot of content here, I still have plenty more to do, and you can create your own content too (finding your own lines etc.) if that’s your kind of thing but this is one to pick up on a sale of at least 50% off.VerdictSteep is a niche game and it doesn’t come without issues but it’s an incredibly enjoyable game that takes you from exhilarating wingsuit challenges, dipping and diving down cliff-sides, to relaxing snowboard rides through a snow-covered forest. It’s well worth picking up on sale whether it’s the kind of game you’d usually play or if you’re looking for something a tad different.El K."
