76561197987526601,Recommended,460920,28652034,"Posted: 25 December, 2016",all,UnfriendlyToast,"Disclaimer----First things first to properly play this game you must go to the options and turn tricks safety off. Without doing this the game plays itself. It feels clunky in that you feel a massive disconnect from your player while doing tricks. It wont even let you initiate a trick if it doesn't think you'll land it. In the end if not turned off it just simply isant fun.I feel it is unfortunate that many of the  gripes people have with the game in general attribute it to the tricks safety option being on. Please give it a try without, and be willing to learn how to do tricks on your own.Review---As a game that didn't really catch me in the beta, Steep really surprised me in both gameplay and progression. The physics feel great. Beyond a few glitches here and there regarding loss of momentum, they function wonderfully. The first few times down the mountain I just gained speed and barreled down like a lunatic. As my snowboarder/skier was speeding up he was hitting the bumps faster, and faster. Until I was going so fast that without me properly maneuvering I was tossed like a rag doll from the force of the bump. Some people may be turned off by the harsh reality that you do not have heels of steel and your bones may very well buckle under the force. But I think this adds to the fun, this forces you to manipulate the physics with the terrain. While also keeping a basic idea of what the human body can take in mind. Im personally a huge fan of dieing again and again cause I got impatient and just demanded speed. Falling can be half the fun. Keep in mind Steep is by no means a hard game but it captures the feeling that you can do anything if you can use all the mechanics well enough. And once you learn to properly carve, trick, etc. The game opens up a bit.New events and areas of the mountain can be slowly unlocked by leveling up. You can do this by doing challenges, or simply by playing. You can view all of the events either by using your mountain view(World Map) or browse within your menu to see quickly whats new. When I played I said !♥♥♥♥! that! And scaled the god damn mountain on foot and found a bunch of cool areas right away. This took for ever but I wanted to see what the game was made of right off the bat.I love the option to explore and just get there anyway despite the level requirement to technically fast travel there. The game even rewards you XP for exploring. So I was pleased to see I wasn't limited to grinding early snowboard, or... Any parachute missions for that matter, before getting to the good stuff. (oh yeah, real quick the parachute missions are awful,boring ,and slow...  They just suck it doesn't hurt the game, I just ignore them till I inevitably have to do them). Where as the wing suit is exiting fast and fun. There are a surprising amount of areas that are tucked away that blew my mind when I found them. Be aware one of the best features of the game is the ability to switch to any of the other sports on the fly by simply stopping. Some of the most fun ive had with the wing suit was after being half way down the mountain on a snowboard, just finding a spot that looks nuts. No event, No mission, just pure discovery. Thinking, is this high enough to get enough lift? When it all comes down to it I find myself never using one sport for very long, and this is one of the games biggest strengths. While also being one of its biggest weaknesses. I love the game, Its scratching that skate itch that is oh so hard to reach now a days, but I would love to see some more sports added, purhaps a snowmobile? I feel boredom may loom in the future, but for now its the perfect hot seat game to play with friends. In the end though wanting more is rarely a bad thing, and with the promise of added sports I know ill at least check them out in the future even if I put this game down. It really is the most relaxing game on my list and fills a niche that no other game currently does. Perfect after work, kick back kinda game.-In short the multuiplayer does a good job at making the mountain not a lonely Barron place, by populating areas with random players.The mupltiplayer fuction is great but limited. As far as moment to moment gamplay is concerned it places players randomly (it seems) into your game world. This works pretty well, I find people disappearing and returning sometimes but its not breaking. The game is at its best if you find a group willing to move together. The group up feature works great, simply by tapping x near another player will send a invite, once recieved all they have to do is press x to accept. I would like to have had options to possibly add more players. 4 player max feels a tad small, although I could see the sheer scope and speed of the game limiting the devs. My biggest complaint though is that there apears to be no way to directly compete with your fellow badasses. You can beat high scores and beat race times which is great. But it just doesnt make up for not being able to race neck and neck with another player. down the mountain.Shareing and replays work great but not quite as good as skate. I have not found a way to share more then one run, which is a bit ehh. I will be tinkering with this feature more. Although it comes down to this really is a social game and i found a lot of fun to be found in watching others replays and sharing the expierince.In closing I waited until it was on a $40 sale. Which really I have to say is the perfect price for this game. I feel like I got a great value for the content, I'm still having loads of fun, and at this point would even say if i put it down for good it was worth playing. It is one of the few games that me and my girlfriend can sit down and play for hours without getting bored and for that I thank you UBI soft."
