,Recommended,460920,28192806,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,Lob,"Excellent game!  I bought this mostly for the snowboarding, but the other sports are great as well.  This genre has been neglected for some time, and it's such a relief that Steep delivers.  The day after release, I played for over eight hours straight without a hint of boredom (highly unusual for me).Start with the challenges, but stay for the exploration and sharing features.  It took me a bit over two hours to even start appreciating the scope of this game.  For those complaining about the standard triple-A price tag, this map alone justifies it.  You really can go anywhere, and it is impossible to fully appreciate the map without dropping in hundreds – if not thousands – of times.  I have found nothing but beautiful, diverse, well-crafted areas that are perfect for exploration and creating your own lines.  At the time of this review (about ten hours in-game), I have not even seen most of the map (much less been bored or run out of things to do).  I already know that I will be racking up hundreds of hours with Steep.The trick system does take some time to get used to, but eventually become quite intuitive.  I highly recommend watching the official Ubisoft tutorial videos over on YouTube.  This is a true triple-A title:  fantastic gameplay, well-optimized, bug-free, zero connectivity issues, and excellent graphics.  I have no hesitation supporting it at full price, and will be purchasing any DLC that comes out (assuming it is of the same high quality)."
,Recommended,460920,28979444,Posted: 3 January,all,BurtStanton,"The more time I spend in Steep the more I am enjoying it.  I find I spend most of my time just riding down the mountain with no objective but to relax and explore.  Skiing and snowboarding feel different enough where I find myself picking between the two for certain challenges.  Wingsuit flying is way more fun than I ever thought it would be.  The more difficult wingsuit challenges that send you flying through canyons and around rock formations can be quite tricky and require a lot of trial and error figuring out the correct line to hit the checkpoints.  When you finally get the right line it is supremely satisfying.  Paragliding is the aspect of the game I have spent the least time with and haven't had the same enjoyment as I have with the other 3 sports.  Though with time and practice that may change.  It is very useful for scaling mountain sides and getting up to new spots to ski or wingsuit from.Coming from the SSX series the trick system took several hours to get used to.  I guess you could say it was a ""Steep"" learning curve... for me at least.  You can't prewind for rotations like in SSX, you do your rotations and flips after you have jumped and the timing can be critical.  Timing your jump also seems to be more important here.  Late jumps will really hurt your ability to do any trick at all and early jumps will limit your air time.  Tricks feel more rooted in realism here than SSX and there is nothing along the lines of an uber trick to be found.  All of this makes it so much more satisfying to land a big trick.Challenges are plentiful and varied.  You can participate in freestyle trick competitions looking to get the most points possible.  Variations on this include getting the most point on one jump or getting a big score on a line that may not be so conducive to freestyle riding.  There are free ride challenges in which your objective is to reach the finish line in the most expeditious manner.  Some of them have checkpoints you need to hit while others just have a finish line and it's up to you to find the fastest line possible.  Wingsuit challenges mostly consist of proximity flying and extreme challenges.  Proximity flying nets you point for flying in ""proximity"" to the ground and obstacles.  The extreme challenges are the most fun (to me) as I had mentioned above.  Paraglide challenges I don't have that much experience so I can't really say.  There are also some fun challenges in the vein of SKATE when your objective is to get the worst fall.  You achieve this by getting the most g's inflicted on your rider in a single fall.  I am only 44% through the game so there may be even more challenges out there that I haven't tried yet.  You can also make your own challenges to share with friend simply by riding a line and then sharing it afterwards and setting which type of challenge you'd like it to be.Plenty of gear to collect and customize your riders.  All of the gear is purely cosmetic and don't offer any boosts to your riders like they would in an SSX.  All lot of it you can buy with the in game currency you earn from challenges and some is only unlocked by completing certain Mountain Stories or achieving a certain medal on a challenge.  Gear ranges from normal jackets and pants to some pretty outlandish full costumes.  There is enough there to make your rider look unique out on the slopes.I know a lot of people are comparing this game to the SSX series.  You can't really compare the two as they are very different products but the comparisons are inevitable.  If you are looking for the over the top point fests of say SSX Tricky then this may not be the game you are looking for.  The closest the SSX series comes to what Steep is was SSX 3.  If you, like me, had a lot of fun just starting at the top of the mountain and free riding your way to the bottom, then you'll enjoy Steep's vast open mountain world.Overall a great game so far and I definitely recommend it.TL;DR - If you love winter sports and exploration, definitely check it out.  If you want a trick/point-fest like the SSX games, I'd still recommend it.  There is enough there for freestyle riders and you may find other parts of the game you enjoy."
