,Not Recommended,460920,29346936,Posted: 18 January,all,Laser Bear,"Steep is a difficult game to assess. Despite putting 40+ hours into the game I would say that I've enjoyed less than 4 of those hours. For me, the biggest failing of the game is that despite being open-world, most challenges lock you into a fixed route where you must pass through a bunch of checkpoints. These challenges are tedious and repetative, unless you enjoy memorizing lines and repeating/refining them.However, Steep excels when it gets out of its own way and lets you be creative about the line you take. Unfortunately, maybe 10% of the missions give you just a start and end point, and leave what is inbetween up to you. One of the best ones is a multi-minute epic ride across multiple faces and ridges, but I have yet to encounter another challenge like it.Overall I would say that Steep is far less enjoyable than Amped 2 was; which the last snowboarding game I played.Pros:It has some impressive graphics, particularly the lighting effects.The wingsuit and hang-glider are interesting additions to an extreme sports game.Some of the challenges are really fun; or very rewarding to pull off.Large area to ride through.Almost no loading time when teleporting around the mountains.Cons:Most of the challenges are boring/repetative.Controls were very sluggish/unresponsive.- Note: I was using an XBOX 360 controller, which I've used for a fair number of Steam games, but Steep seemed to ignore diagonal input entirely.Using both sticks to control turning is an interesting concept, but was not a good design decision.I was unable to use the character customization screen for more than a minute due to lag (eventually crashing the program).Edit: I forgot to mention that the soundtrack is very limited, particularly compared to the Amped franchise."
