,Recommended,460920,30764241,Posted: 26 March,all,EightSkull,"I've played about 10 hours of this in the first 2 days of buying it and I'm very happy with the purchase.  I bought the Gold Edition, which I recommend, because it gives you access to more terrain which you will probably want.  Although the Alps (included with base game) is an incredibly vast area that could take you months to explore.  I feel that I've barely scratched the surface of the available terrain in the Alps.  This is the most fun I've had in a winter sports game since1080 Snowboardingfor the Nintendo 64.  It really captures the feel of skiing/snowbarding in deep powder.If you're looking for a game with a highly structured campaign, keep looking. This is an open-world, sandbox with the fun you get out of it being highly dependent on your own sense of adventure.  There are plenty of well set-up races and wingsuit jumps with checkpoints and opponents to keep you busy with structured events -- but be prepared to go exploring if you want to get the most out of this game.  Multiplayer is a blast, with the ability to group with three other people and take on the mountain.  You will find plenty of random strangers, sometimes in the middle of nowhere, willing to group with you.  It really adds a nice feel seeing other people doing the same lines you are doing.At 1440p on a 144Hz monitor, this game flogs my 1070-based system.  I'm not running on ultra settings, I had to take it down to ""high"" and turn all AA off to get 60-80 FPS.  Then I turned resolution scaling down to 0.9 so that I could get consistent FPS above 100, which is where I like it.  It still looks AMAZING and part of what makes the adventure on the mountain(s) so fun is the beauty of it all, with dynamic day/night cycles.The #1 complaint about this game coming out of the Steam reviews is the price. I got the Gold Edition on Steam Sale for $40 (50% off regular price) and I think that's more or less fair for a game that's only been out for four months.  I would not pay $80 for the Gold Edition."
