,Recommended,460920,29328460,Posted: 17 January,all,Yellin' Screamin' Gordon Freeman,"I like it a lot, but I'm also a sucker for snowsports games. Reaching the level cap of 25 can be done pretty quickly, but actually doing every challenge (especially up to gold medal standards) will take a while unless you've entirely mastered the physics system and memorized every mountain face.Pros:-Huge amount of mountain terrain to explore with lots of unmarked stuff to find-Visually beautiful-Skiing and snowboarding have subtle differences that make each of them worth trying-Soundtrack is well-designed for snowsports with a good variety-Challenges are usually easy enough to get in one try-Replay editing makes you feel like an amateur Warren MillerCons:-Always online means you better be sure your connection is steady at all times-Multiplayer feels a bit tacked on, haven't really seen any sort of reason to play with others unless you really need a score multiplier boost-Physics are occasionally inconsistent, but no more so than Skate or any other extreme sports game-Not enough music in the soundtrack, you will hear repeats very often when you're restarting a challenge-Controls take a bit to get used to, mostly due to automapping the jump/ollie function to controller triggers-No grindable surfaces, which feels a bit glaring considering almost every extreme sports game has had this-Season Pass is not worth the price, and it's arguable that the base game price is a bit steep *badump tish*If you're looking for a game where you make your own fun setting up lines and editing your footage, then Steep is certainly going to give you a lot of playtime and material to work with. If you're looking for a next-generation SSX game, then you'd better keep looking."
